---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { site } from "@/data/site";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="OPNsense, Home Assistant, and One Brittle Button - Arjun Pherwani"
  description="A build-log note about replacing an old TP-Link router with an OPNsense mini PC, then experimenting with Home Assistant routine automation."
  type="article"
  publishedTime="2026-06-13T12:00:00.000Z"
  tags={["OPNsense", "Home Assistant", "networking", "automation"]}
>
  <article>
    <header class="prose-wrap page-header">
      <p class="mono">Build log 001 / home network</p>
      <h1 class="log-title">OPNsense, Home Assistant, and One Brittle Button</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        I needed to upgrade an old TP-Link router, bought a cheap fanless mini PC,
        and ended up with a small home-lab path that is weirdly close to software-defined
        networking at work.
      </p>
      <div class="project-meta">
        <span>OPNsense</span>
        <span>Home Assistant</span>
        <span>Hue</span>
        <span>router-level adblocking</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="prose-wrap prose log">
      <h2 class="sub">Goal</h2>
      <p>
        Replace an aging TP-Link router without spending actual network-appliance money, get
        router-level adblocking, and start building a home setup that can eventually isolate IoT
        devices and experiments on their own network.
      </p>

      <h2 class="sub">Setup</h2>
      <div class="diagram" aria-label="Home network and automation setup">
        <div class="dgm-row">
          <span class="dgm-box">Cable modem</span>
          <span class="dgm-arr">-&gt;</span>
          <span class="dgm-box">Shuttle DS68U</span>
          <span class="dgm-arr">-&gt;</span>
          <span class="dgm-box">OPNsense</span>
          <span class="dgm-arr">-&gt;</span>
          <span class="dgm-box">TP-Link AP mode</span>
        </div>
        <div class="dgm-row">
          <span class="dgm-box">Hue button</span>
          <span class="dgm-arr">-&gt;</span>
          <span class="dgm-box">Home Assistant</span>
          <span class="dgm-arr">-&gt;</span>
          <span class="dgm-box">routine state</span>
          <span class="dgm-arr">-&gt;</span>
          <span class="dgm-box">Echo announcement</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The router box was a used Shuttle DS68U: fanless, Intel Celeron 3855U, dual Intel gigabit
        LAN, tiny 1.3-liter body, and a very digital-signage-looking I/O panel. It cost about
        $50 plus shipping and tax. I flashed OPNsense onto it and moved the old TP-Link into access
        point mode.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second box was a used Cryo mini PC with an i3-7100U, 4GB DDR4, 120GB NVMe, fanless
        aluminum case, and dual RTL8111E gigabit LAN. I was not as lucky on price, but it was still
        a useful Home Assistant box. I flashed Home Assistant onto it and connected it to my Philips
        Hue bulbs.
      </p>

      <h2 class="sub">Worked</h2>
      <div class="block ok">
        <span class="block-tag">Router</span>
        <p>
          Flashing OPNsense was smooth. The DS68U became the router, the TP-Link became the AP, and
          router-level adblocking worked. For a cheap eBay mini PC, that was a very satisfying
          result.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="block ok">
        <span class="block-tag">Routine button</span>
        <p>
          Home Assistant could track a daily routine state and advance it from a Hue Smart Button.
          A separate automation announced the current block through an Echo Dot whenever the state
          changed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <pre class="snippet"><code>Hue button -&gt; input_select.current_block -&gt; input_text.current_task -&gt; Echo announcement</code></pre>

      <h2 class="sub">Failed</h2>
      <div class="block bad">
        <span class="block-tag">AP mode</span>
        <p>
          The OPNsense side was boring in the good way. The TP-Link AP-mode experience was the fussy
          part and needed a couple resets before it behaved.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="block bad">
        <span class="block-tag">Routine model</span>
        <p>
          The Home Assistant routine kind of worked, but it is brittle. It encodes the day as a long
          hand-written chain of states: Wake, Run, Breakfast, Work Block 1, Work Block 2, Lunch,
          Work Block 3, Work Wrap, Evening, Journal, Bed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <pre class="snippet"><code>Work Block 1 -&gt; Work Block 2 -&gt; Lunch Prep -&gt; Lunch -&gt; Work Block 3</code></pre>

      <h2 class="sub">Changed</h2>
      <p>
        The router upgrade changed the home network from a consumer-router box into a small
        firewall/router setup I can understand and modify. The automation experiment also clarified
        something: automating decision-making is not the same as hardcoding a perfect day and asking
        a button to advance it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The funny part is that this puts me in the neighborhood of software-defined networking at
        home and at work, just at wildly different scales.
      </p>

      <h2 class="sub">Next</h2>
      <div class="block next">
        <span class="block-tag">Network</span>
        <p>
          Buy a UniFi U7 Pro or U7 Lite so I can use VLAN tagging and put IoT devices and home-lab
          projects on a separate network.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="block next">
        <span class="block-tag">Automation</span>
        <p>
          Rethink the routine automation so it is less brittle. The useful idea is environment
          support for work decisions; the current implementation is too much of a fixed script.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="endlinks">
        <a class="inline-link" href="/log/">All build logs</a>
        <a class="inline-link" href="/projects/">Projects</a>
      </div>

      <p class="mono faint" style="margin-top: 28px;">
        Last updated {site.lastUpdated}.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
